        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>This project has three scientific goals: 1) search for mm/sub-mm jet and polarized emission from Sgr A*, 2) time delay in the sub-mm and 3) determining the peak in the SED.  We are not S/N limited, but require enough time to observe sufficient parallactic angle coverage needed to calibrate out instrumental polarization (3 hr), which will also acquire good visibility coverage to adequately image near Sgr A* as well. In particular, we intend to use one pointing on Sgr A* and observe in three different bands. The images obtained from these observations match well with the range of scales of the jet detected with the VLA at wavelengths ranging between 6cm and 7mm. Given that the VLA is a linear array, deconvolution errors result in linear structures in the residual beam pattern. Imaging with ALMA should establish the reality of the linear structure.  To determine time delays of a flare we will compare light curves from one baseband relative to another in the other sideband in the same band. 

This scheduling block in Band 3 will observe 100 GHz continuum in full polarization.  We will leverage the 3 hr total duration required to obtain parallactic angle coverage for polarization calibration to remove instrumental polarization to obtain dense visibility coverage for imaging. The flaring of Sgr A* is known to vary from minute to hourly time scales at radio and sub-mm wavelengths. By comparing a light curve from lowest frequency baseband at 89.5-91.5 GHz to one at 103.5-105.5 GHz, we can get very high sensitivity (about 0.3 mJy rms in 30 seconds) and wide frequency coverage 14 GHz simultaneously, instead of the traditional way of multiplexing observing frequencies.  We request a 3 hour scheduling block -- the minimum necessary for polarization calibration.  These observations are *not* time constrained.  

To image any jet emission, we need high resolution observations and request 0.451 arcsecond resolution.  These observations are unique in their ability to potentially detect the base of jet very close to Sgr A*.  The base of the jet we are looking for would be small (&lt; 5) arcseconds, which is less than 1/3 of the primary beam size, which is the area where ALMA can image polarized emission due to the fact that off-axis instr polarization is known to vary with position. </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
