    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>One of the key questions related to the nature of emission from Sgr A* is whether there is a jet or an outflow emanating from this source. The evidence for a jet from Sgr A* has a direct bearing on models of broad band emission and the accretion rate onto Sgr A*. We have recently studied radio continuum emission from the region surrounding Sgr A* and have tentatively detected a symmetric linear feature from Sgr A* which appears to be partially polarized on a scale of few arcseconds from Sgr A*.  We propose to use the unique capabilities of ALMA to image the inner few arcseconds of Sgr A* in total and polarized intensity and establish the detection of a jet as well as determining the rotation measure of polarized radiation in three bands. The proposed observations will also characterize the variable emission from Sgr A* across each of the three bands 3, 6 and 7 as well as to  determine the SED of the quiescent emission. These measurements will determine the collimated mass outflow rate, accretion rate from rotation measure measurements, test the prediction of  time delay within ALMA bands and determine the transition wavelength at which the emission becomes optically thin.

</prp:abstract>
